text: hi everyone anthony fantano here
internet's busiest music nerd and this
is a review of the new dark side album
psychic dark side is the musical duo of
david harrington and new york-based
electronic music producer nicholas jarre
who you may be familiar with if you've
been watching the reviews for a while
because he has made some of my favorite
electronic music of the past few years i
was pretty psyched to listen to this new
album even though maybe i wasn't head
over heels for the ep that darkseid
dropped on nicholas jars clown and
sunset label but as a duo darkseid under
the name daftside did put out a
strangely interesting and oddly creative
remix album a track for track remix of
the new daft punk album titling at
random access memories memories and even
though the remix album wasn't track for
track amazing it said to me at least
that dark side was evolving into
something a project that wasn't afraid
to take a risk and just kind of do
something a little left field and give
fans something a little unexpected and
maybe unexpected sums up a little of the
music on this album too like i
anticipated from darkseid and just from
a nicholas jar project in general i feel
like this record in a way fits squarely
into that micro house wagon and of
course the overall vibe and aesthetic of
the sounds on this lp are very nocturnal
they're shadowy but i think this record
takes those characteristics and just
turns them in a different direction
while the beats and the grooves on this
album are sort of subtle and spacious
there is a pretty over rock vibe that
bleeds through on most of the tracks
here for one the song paper trails with
its percussion with its guitar lines as
well as its vocals
there was a bit of a doors influence
radiating off of this track from the
first moment i heard it and whether the
influence is intentionally being shown
off or not it's still a great track i
love the bluesy guitar licks that dave
brings into the fold as the song is
building nicholas jarre's vocal phrasing
seems very jim morrison inspired maybe a
bit of a scott walker vibe in the over
vibrato in his singing and there's this
weird based chorus effect behind his
voice kind of adding this just
unsettling unnerving characteristic to
the vocals on this track that while they
were weird the first few times i heard
it i sort of have grown to love it with
repeat listens i also love the subtle
keyboards hanging in the background that
sort of pop in against the chorus around
the 2 30 mark of this song it's a really
beautiful track overall one of the most
melodically interesting songs that i
think nicholas jar has been involved
with so far i would say that the song
heart 2 has a rock vibe in it with its
crispier drums as well as its trudging
and slowly descending chord progression
with the guitar melodies echoing this
really obvious rock influence from the
60s and from the 70s i would actually
even say the melodies and the chord
progressions on the closing track here
are a little floydian still even though
darkseid does embrace a rock direction
on this lp i would not say this album in
any way is is in your face or incredibly
upbeat it's still a slow burner it's
still a record that requires a lot of
patience there's really nothing that
says you need an attention span for this
record like an 11 minute opening track
the way this opener kicks off with these
really warm kind of sporadic
synthesizers there's a really just ear
tickling fuzzy drone hanging in the
background that i like a lot and with
this rock steady beat just kind of
subtly pulsating away in the background
this to me feels more like something i
would just expect from nicholas jarr but
this moment in the song is merely the
intro after 4 minutes and 30 seconds
dave harrington brings in these really
dry prickly guitar leads that just kind
of bounce and plink around the mix i
love the heavy groove that this song
sort of flows into toward the finish as
well as the build that's backed up with
some really high pitched synths it sort
of explodes and dissipates fizzles a
little bit and then floats on this very
textured outro it's a fantastically
structured song stays engaging from
beginning to end and nearly every other
song on here is engaging from beginning
to end too i think the most lackluster
and maybe least memorable songs on this
lp are the two shorter tracks on here
that kind of feel like intermissions
maybe i was looking for a little bit
more from the song on greek light though
the song does fall just short of three
minutes and it's a kind of interesting
three minutes with these
somewhat kitschy keyboards playing a
very mournful set of chords and then
these vocals are laid on top which are
incredibly odd and maybe that's another
thing i need to sort of make note of
with this record a lot of tracks on here
feature vocals and many of them are are
not sung in a very traditional way to go
back to the song heart there's a very
awkward and strange falsetto over a
majority of that track and the track the
only shrine i've ever seen has these
falsettos and maybe some mid-range
vocals doubled up on top of each other
for a pretty strange listening
experience that that i actually liked a
lot also the watery and very sharp
rhythm guitars on this track kind of
leave me feeling like nicholas and david
really did take the disco direction that
daft punk took their new album in to
heart overall not a lot of complaints
about this record a few songs on here
most notably the shorter ones paled in
comparison to others but still nicholas
and dave came together on this album and
made a series of tracks that are
intensely hypnotic low-key and very
detailed with layers of instrumentation
and some pretty interesting textures too
especially at the beginning of a track
like freak go home which which is mostly
an instrumental song that is chock full
of all of these odd samples that that
really could have been lifted from
anywhere sort of reminds me of his live
sets when he samples radio noise or
radio static i am feeling a strong eight
on this album transition but if you've
given this dark side album a listen what
did you think of it did you love it hate
it why what do you think i should review
next and
that's it
darkseid
psychic
forever
